'''Sumiyoshi-shō''' (住吉荘) was a {{ill|shōen|ja|荘園|12=draft|12=draft}} (manorial estate) located in {{ill|Azumi District, Shinano Province|ja|安曇郡|12=draft|12=draft}} (modern-day {{ill|Azumino, Nagano|ja|安曇野市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Nagano Prefecture). The estate was situated on the fan-shaped land formed by the confluence of the {{ill|Azusa River|ja|梓川|en|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Kurosawa River (Nagano)|ja|黒沢川|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== History == During the late {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, under the {{ill|insei|ja|院政|12=draft|12=draft}} system, the estate was donated to {{ill|Emperor Go-Shirakawa|ja|Emperor Go-Shirakawa|12=draft|12=draft}} by the Nishimaki clan, a branch of the {{ill|Shigeno clan|ja|滋野氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, who were local ruling developers. The estate’s administrative rights were passed from {{ill|Takasina Eiko|ja|高階栄子|12=draft|12=draft}}, one of the emperor’s consorts, to {{ill|Princess Kinshi|ja|覲子内親王|12=draft|12=draft}} (Sen'yōmon-in), and later entrusted to {{ill|Yamashina Tokonari|ja|山科教成|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>“Japanese Shōen Studies, Vol. 5” (1989, Yoshikawa Kōbunkan), p.283.</ref> The {{ill|Sumiyoshi Shrine (Azumino)|ja|住吉神社|12=draft|12=draft}} was established as the general guardian shrine for the estate’s 18 villages, and {{ill|Heifukuji (Azumino)|ja|平福寺|12=draft|12=draft}} was built within its grounds.
By the {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, the name of the estate appeared in the {{ill|Azuma Kagami|ja|吾妻鏡|12=draft|12=draft}} on the entry for {{ill|March 12, 1186|ja|文治2nd year 3月12日|12=draft|12=draft}}. At this time, markets were established in the estate’s villages, such as Ichinichi Market and Nanoka Market in Futagi Village and Muika Market in Nakakaya Village, forming bustling market towns. In 1191 (Kenkyū 2), the estate became part of the {{ill|Chōkōdō estates|ja|長講堂領|12=draft|12=draft}} and was responsible for supplying resources for annual rituals. The Chōkōdō imposed military duties on its estates, with guards stationed at Yōbai Gate, where Sumiyoshi-shō contributed three soldiers monthly.<ref>“Nagano Prefectural History, Vol. 2” (Nagano Prefecture, 1989), p.400.</ref>
In 1335 (Kenmu 2), during the {{ill|Nanboku-chō period|ja|南北朝時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, the estate was confiscated from its Southern Court administrator, the Ōtsuma clan, and granted to the Northern Court's {{ill|Shinano Governor|ja|信濃守護|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ogasawara Sadamune|ja|小笠原貞宗|12=draft|12=draft}}, becoming a key part of the Northern Court's domain alongside Haruchika Territory. During the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, conflicts between the Shigeno clans, including the Nishimaki and Ōtsuma clans, and the Ogasawara clan continued. The estate participated in the {{ill|Ōtō Battle|ja|大塔合戦|12=draft|12=draft}} in 1400 (Ōei 7). After the defeat of {{ill|Ogasawara Nagahide|ja|小笠原長秀|12=draft|12=draft}}, the estate temporarily became an imperial domain but was returned to {{ill|Ogasawara Masayasu|ja|小笠原政康|12=draft|12=draft}} in 1425 (Ōei 25) by decree of {{ill|Ashikaga Yoshimochi|ja|足利義持|12=draft|12=draft}}.
At one point, the estate was administered by [[:en:Prince_Fushimi_Yoshihito|Prince Fushimi Yoshihito]] and {{ill|Prince Sadafusa of Fushimi|ja|伏見宮貞成親王|12=draft|12=draft}}, creating disputes with the Yamashina family. During the {{ill|Bunmei era|ja|文明|12=draft|12=draft}}, the estate was under the administration of {{ill|Yamashina Norikuni|ja|山科言国|12=draft|12=draft}}, who appointed Minamoto Kiyoyuki as an overseer. Records in the {{ill|Norikuni-kyo Diary|ja|言国卿記|12=draft|12=draft}} mention monetary payments of annual tributes through currency exchange. Even during the {{ill|Sengoku period|ja|戦国時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, the estate’s annual tribute exceeded 1,000 kanmon, marking it as a significant estate. It also repeatedly provided labor for the construction of {{ill|Suwa Taisha|ja|諏訪大社|1=Suwa-taisha|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Hotaka Shrine|ja|穂高神社|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== References == <references/>
== Further Reading == * “Historical Atlas of Nagano Prefecture” (Heibonsha, 1979) * “Japanese Historical Dictionary, Vol. 8” (Yoshikawa Kōbunkan, 1989) * “Kadokawa Japanese Place Name Dictionary, Vol. 20: Nagano Prefecture” (Kadokawa Shoten, 1990) * “Nagano Prefectural History, Vol. 2: Medieval Period 1”
{{Japanese-history-stub}}
